  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How many people work at Manila's Entertainment City integrated resorts?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Manila's Entertainment City employs approximately 32,000 people directly across its four operational integrated resorts (Solaire, City of Dreams, Okada Manila, and Westside City). An additional 8,000 to 12,000 workers are employed through outsourced service contracts for cleaning, security, food preparation, and maintenance. The total workforce, including outsourced labor, is estimated at 40,000 to 44,000 people.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the average salary for integrated resort workers in the Philippines?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Entry-level positions such as cleaners, utility workers, and kitchen assistants typically earn PHP 16,770 to PHP 19,000 per month. Dealers earn PHP 22,000 to PHP 28,000 per month including pooled tips. Kitchen staff earn PHP 18,000 to PHP 24,000 depending on specialization and seniority. These wages are close to or slightly above the Metro Manila minimum wage but are significantly below comparable positions in the BPO industry, which typically pay PHP 28,000 to PHP 38,000 for similar experience levels.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What are the working conditions like for casino workers in Manila?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Published research from the University of the Philippines found that IR workers reported an average of 5.2 hours of sleep per night on work days, compared to 6.8 hours for Metro Manila workers overall. The majority live in Cavite, Laguna, or Bulacan with one-way commutes averaging 90 minutes. Graveyard shift workers face additional challenges including disrupted circadian rhythms, limited public transportation options during predawn hours, and high motorcycle taxi costs that can consume up to half of their take-home pay.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How much revenue do Manila's integrated resorts generate?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Manila's licensed casinos, led by Entertainment City's integrated resorts, generated PHP 44.52 billion in gross gaming revenue in Q1 2026 alone, representing 50.83% of total Philippine GGR. This makes Entertainment City one of the highest-grossing casino districts in Asia. The four resorts collectively contribute billions in taxes, fees, and contributions to the Philippine government through PAGCOR.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Are there labor protections specific to casino workers in the Philippines?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Casino workers are covered by the Philippine Labor Code and DOLE regulations, including minimum wage, overtime pay, and holiday premium standards. However, there are no industry-specific labor guidelines for integrated resort workers. PAGCOR Chairman Tengco acknowledged during a March 2026 Senate hearing that draft welfare guidelines for IR workers had not yet been published, despite being discussed since 2024. Labor groups have called for the regularization of outsourced workers and for IR-specific protections addressing shift work, commute costs, and sleep deprivation.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

